{"/service/ndnp/ohi/batch_ohi_goyle_ver01/data/sn82007637/00516993832/1957100401/0010.xml":{"full_text":"THE\nUNION\nJOURNAL\u2019S\nEditorial Page\nFriday, October 4,1957\nSame Old Chamber\nUE GOT A LINE UP of speakers for\nV V the annual state convention of the\nOhio Chamber of Commerce next month\nand handed it to a retired baseball scout\nwe know, and asked him for a report.\nWe got the report this week. Here's what\nit said\u2014\n\u201cChamber convention line-up loaded\nwith right-handers. Line-up features such\nswingers as U. S. Senator Carl T. Curtis,\nup from the Republican league in Nebras\nka Washington scouts rate him one of the\nmost anti-labor members of the Senate.\nHe teamed up with Senator Barry Gold\nwater on bill to prohibit political activity\nby unions.\n\u201cBehind Curtis is a senator from a\nlower league, the Indiana State Legisla\nture. Name is D Russell Bontrager. Per\nfect batting record in Anti-Labor League;\nsponsored right-to-work bill adopted by\nlast Indiana Legislature\n\u201cOver from Notre Dame University is\nthe Rev. Edward A Keller, one of few\nCatholic priests to support right to-work\nlaws Also a former third baseman by the\nname of Frank J Lausche, now with Sen\nators in Washington, and John W. Brick\ner, who caught for Ohio State in his col\nlege days. He and Lausche make good hit\nand-run combination.\n\u201cAlso in line u is William L McGrath,\nhead of Williamson Company of Cincin\nnati, home of Cincinnati Reds Has a com\nplex about the Reds; looks under bed be\nfora retiring to see if any present. Not a\nteam player, prefers to go it alone.\n\"Team captain is Herschel C Atkin\nson, Executive Vice President of Cham\nber. Good leader but leans too heavily on\nright handers. Plans to talk on \u2018Right-to\nWork Situation in Ohio\n\u201cConclusion: Over-all team strength\nfairly good. Records show, however, that\nsuch teams seldom win pennant\nOur scouting friend didn\u2019t put this in\nhis report but he commnented it was ob\nvious to him the Chamber would he\nswinging hard at organized labor. He\nadded that the Chamber\u2019s strategy was\nunfortunate since the record in \"right\nto work\" states shows that such laws\nharm the entire economy of the state, not\njust the workers They mean low wages\nand less purchasing power\nIn other words, he concluded, the\nChamber\u2019s strategy not only eliminates\nany pennant hopes but also means less\nbusiness at the box office.\nToo\nHigh A Price!\nS THE NATIONAL Administration ac\ntually planning a \u201clittle recession\u201d to\nI\nfight inflation? There is increasing specu\nlation that the answer is \u201cyes.\u201d\nThe New York Journal of. Commerce\nsays the evidence shows that \u201cboth the\nAdministration and the Federal Reserve\nauthorities believe that a \u2018moderate re\ncession now\u2019 would be a small price to\npay\u201d to avoid a depression later.\nThe syndicated financial columnist,\nSylvia Porter, writes that in off-the-rec\nord talks with top government policy\nmakers she has heard again and again\nthat what we need to end inflation \u201cis a\nlittle recession, and the quicker it comes\nthe better.\u201d\nThe magazine U S News World\nReport says the cycle of inflation may be\nburning out and that we\u2019ll see a little\nslowing here and there But \u201cnothing\nreally serious in an over-all way though,\u201d\nit adds.\n\u201cWhat\u2019s happening has been planned\nand the plans appear to be working,\u201d the\nmagazine commented (Underlining ours)\nAnd added to all this is the statement\nlast month by former Secretary of the\nTreasury George Humphrey that \u201cthe\nhappiest thing that can happen to this\ncountry\" is a drop in production.\nThese comments seem to indicate that\nif Administration officials haven\u2019t actual\nly launched a definite plan to put a crimp\nin the economy, at least some of them are\nhoping for a slow-down\nWe all would like to see a halt to the\ninflationary spiral. But not at the price\nof a recession. A recession means people\nORGANIZE TOLEDO 100%\nOfficial Publication of Organized Labor\nin Northwestern Ohio\nEntered at Toledo, Ohio, Post Office as second\nclass matter under the act of Aug 24, 1912\nPublished Every Friday\nPublishing Office, 425 Winthrop Street\nToledo, Ohio\nFor Information Phone CH. 1-9126\nWalter Murphy\nBernard Stern\nWilliam Borden\nDerele Collins\nMelvin Zimkowski,\nEdmond A Pawlicki\nEditor\nAssociate Editor\nSports Editor\nCirculation Manager\nJournal Cameramen\nOrville Beemer, Walter Murphy,\nCharles Ballard, Otto Beebe (Local 348),\nErnest Love (Local 1058) Board of Trustees\nDavid Saber\nDirector of Advertising\nTelephone Advertising Department\nCH. 4-4400 and CH. 6-1141\nMember Trade Union Advertising, N. T.\nout of work and less food on the table.\nIt\u2019s too high a price.\nAnd it\u2019s difficult to believe that some\nof the top people in the Eisenhower Ad\nministration are willing to pay that price.\nBut what we\u2019ve been reading indicates\nthat they are.\nThose Defense Cuts\nSWINGER OF THE meanest economy\naxe in Washington these days is De\nfense Secretary Charles Wilson. With the\nblessing of President Eisenhower, Wilson\nhas just ordered another 100,000-man cut\nin the armed forces.\nWilson said the cut would eliminate\nanother five Air Force wings, one Army\ndivision and 35 Navy ships. This is the\nsecond 100,000 man cut in two months.\nAnd Wilson said still another military\nmanpower reduction is \u201cunder study.\u201d\nWilson admitted there has been no\nchange in the world situation to warrant\nsuch reductions but commented that the\nAmerican people \u201cseem to want\u201d Gov\nernment spending reduced. Nonsense,\nCharley.\nThe people want needless spending\nstopped but since when have the Ameri\ncan people refused to support an ade\nquate defense for our country.\nWe might remind Wilson and the\nPresident of some recent statements by\nDwight D. Eisenhower. We recall these:\n\u201cI have seen unwise military cuts before.\nI have seen their terrible consequences;\u201d\n\u201cThe plain truth is that the price of peace\nis high;\" and, \u201cThere is no cut price for\nsecurity.\u201d\nWilson also tried to explain the cuts\nby saying that the country\u2019s military\nstrength is getting more powerful all the\ntime. This prompted the Washington Post\nand Times Herald to ask, \u201cDoes Mr. Wil\nson really mean that the more we cut the\nstronger we become?\u201d\nThat\u2019s about the same as telling the\nRussians, \u201cOne step closer and we\u2019ll cut\nour armed forces another 100,000.\u201d\nGOP NATIONAL Chairman Mead Al\ncorn says the GOP will have an \u201copen\u201d\nconvention in 1960, same as in 1956\nTell it to Joe Smith!\nVandercook Says:\n(Thu column is excerpted from the\nnightly broadcasts of John W. Vander\ncook, ABC commentator, sponsored by the\nAFL-CIO. Listen to Vandercook over the\nABC network Monday through Friday at\n10 p.m., EST.)\nA\nRKANSAS Gov. Fau bus\u2019 rebellion\nagainst the Constitution has had only\nthe most unhappy effect upon the pres\ntige and reputation of the United States.\nNo American of any political persuasion\nfinds any particle of satisfaction in that.\nFaubus' move was singularly ill-timed.\nFor the first time in three generations, a\nsession of Congress had just ended during\nwhich, at long last, the truth was recog\nnized that the South's long-cherished tra\ndition of segregation must henceforth be\nmodified; eventually, would have to he\n'abandoned.\nFor the first time since the Civil War,\nwith the sole exception of South Caro\nlina\u2019s Sen. Thurmond, deep-South legisla\ntors were made aware that they would\nmerely waste their breath by attempting\nto defeat a civil rights bill by filibuster.\nThe climate of opinion had changed. When\nthe final vote on the far from negligible\nright-to-vote bill was taken, even Texans\nvoted \"yes.\u201d\nHarry S. Truman, characteristically,\nspoke swiftly and to the point. The issue\nin Arkansas, as the ex President saw it,\nwas between right and wrong. And Fau\nbus was wrong.\nEqually quick in condemnation of Fau\nbus, was the Democratic National Advis\nory Council. Nor has Democratic National\nChairman Paul Butler hesitated in ex\npressing his convictions.\nNone of those Democratic spokesmen\ngave the impression that they first took\ncare, before they spoke, to test which way\nthe political winds were blowing. Rather,\nthey appear simply to have expressed\ntheir personal belief When political\nleaders do that, in a free and decent land\nthey, and the party to which they belong,\ngrow, alike, in stature.\n\ne\n\nEC. OF DEFENSE Wilson announces\nk\nthat he will pass another miracle. For\nfinancial reasons\u2014since his department\nis still outrunning the sums appropriated\nfor it by Congress\u2014Wilson is going to\nreduce the U. S. armed forces by another\n100,060 men. The Air Force will lose four\nmore \u201cwings,\u201d the Army will have to rid\nitself of still another division, and the\nNavy will have to lay up more ships.\nBut, says Wilson, all that can be done\n\u201cwithout impairment of our national se\ncurity.\u201d The hard fact is, the defense sec\nretary points out, that the administra\ntion's spending has brought it so close to\nthe legal (and probably far too low, too\nout-of-date, and too rigidly fixed) national\ndebt limit, that \"the Treasury can\u2019t even\nborrow the money.\u201d\nGENERAL\nWELFARE\nwcats\nCopright 1953\u2014re nntmim\n1\nIMMIWWMTWTWMFWE\"MTTWFTNTTMIRTCAFI!TTTWTTHTTHY\"TTT\"YHTTY\"\"TT\"THTYT:T\"TTTTYT\"\"FTWY\u00ae\"TTT\"YWTHT\"YTMMTTTTTMM:P\"TE\"TTTN\"TTTTMYTTTTVY\"TVTTY\"I/THF:TN:\"CTTMTTF\"\":\"\"MW\nBusiness Trends:\nBusiness Fears Boom Wearing Out\n.THWHWYFMTITMTMKHi MMMMMMWIitlim\nThe following report on the outlook of\nbusiness has been prepared by the Research\nDepartment of the Federal Reserve Bank of\nCleveland.\n\n\nSEPTEMBER, the first month of the fall\nbusiness season, is now passing into his\ntory. It appears that September will turn out\nto have been another strong month as to the\nfacts and figures of business activity, as well\nas being another month of perplexing anxiety\nabout the business outlook\nThere have been, indeed, many months\nduring the past year or so when the business\nfacts have been stronger than the tone of\nbusiness opinion. What is the nature of the\ngeneral worries which today surround the\nbusiness outlook? There seem to be two basic\nworries, neither of which is new, they have\npersisted during a considerable part of the\npostwar span of years.\nOne is the fear that the business boom will\n\u201cwear out\", i.e., that the present high level of\nactivity will be succeeded by slump and con\nsiderable unemployment. The second is the\nbasic anxiety about inflation the fear that\nrising prices and rising costs will continue and\nwill sooner or later get out of hand.\nDo these two worries cancel each other\nout? The answer depends upon the timing of\nthe outlook period under consideration. Thus,\nif a person is talking about the prospects for\nthe fourth quarter of this year, it is hardly\nlogical to be concerned both about the pros\npect of inflation and recession. In general, the\ntwo kinds of outlook are mutually exclusive.\nOver a longer period of time, however, the\ntwo sources of concern are not mutually ex\nclusive; in fact, they tend to coalesce. That is,\nserious inflation usually leads to a setback in\nthe form of reduced activity and unemploy\nment. It is first one, and then the other. This\neconomic aftermath of inflation is one aspect\nof its menace; the other basic aspect is the so\ncial consequences associated with the impact\nof inflation upon various groups of the com\nmunity.\nTHE BASIC FEAR that the boom will\nwear out has persisted for about ten years\nwith little or no realization in actual fact, ex\ncept perhaps for the extremely moderate re\ncessions of 1949 and 1934 This anxiety, how\never, takes different shapes and forms at dif\nferent times. Thus, at present, there is a spec\nific anxiety in many business quarters about\nthe prospective impact of the cuts in defense\nspending which have been announced by gov\nernmental authorities, at least in the form of\na general intention. There is also some spec\nific concern about the leveling tendencies\n(and a possibility of future reduction) in the\nvolume of business outlays for new plant and\nThrough The Years\nWith The Toledo Union Journal\nOCTOBER 3, 1947: PAC's registration and\nvote drive was continued this week with all\nworkers urged to go to the Board of Elections\nor to one of the conveniently located neigh\nborhood places to become eligible to vote in\nthe November elections Walter Reuther,\nUAW-CIO President, told a union rally Tues\nday night to \u201cfight on the union front, the\nconsumer front and the political front1\u2019 if work\ners were to make full use of their great power\nPrices are leveling off at a point about 28\nper cent above a year ago, the Bureau of La\nbor Statistics repoted\nOCTOBER 1, 1952: Rent Control, about\nten years old, died Wednesday in Toledo be\ncause six Councilmen voted to wipe out rent\ncontrol a few weeks ago Shop chairmen\nof Local 12 Units climaxed a 6-hour meeting\nheld Monday by pledging an all-out campaign\nto help elect Tom Burke to Congress and other\nDemocratic candidates on the state and na\ntional ballot.\nOCTOBER 5, 1956: A sixth UAW shop has\naffiliated with the Willys Unit Diagnostic\nClinic, making the clinic's unparalled facili\nties now available for an estimated 35,000 per\nsons. The J&L Unit of Local 12 concluded\nnegotiations providing them with improved\npension plan, improved vacation, benefits, a\nwage increase of 10.8 cents an hour and other\nbenefits. The brand-new Auto-Lite Credit\nUnion office building will be opened to union\nmembers and to the public for inspection Sun\nday. A total of $259,275 was given by four\nfamilies to the presidential campaign and just\nabout matched the total expense of the AFL\nCIO Committee on Political Education in 1956.\nequipment, which were the source of consid\nerable stimulation to business in 1955 and\n1956. With respect to general inventory accu\nmulation, at the moment there does not seem\nto be quite so much anxiety expressed as was\nthe case some months ago; however, this lat\nter consideration may again come to the fore\nin case defense cut-backs -should be actually\nrealized in substantial quantity.\nIn respect to the general worry over in\nflation, which is the second basic fear, it ap\npears that there are specific ways in which\nthe anxiety is manifested at the present time.\nOne of these ways is embodied in the growing\ndiscussion of \u201ccreeping inflation\u201d. Without\ngoing into details, it may be said that the con\ncept is one which alleges the practical inevi\ntability of a gradual rise in the general price\nlevel. In the explanation of this doctrine by\nits leading advocates, the persistence of a\n\u201csmall\u201d degree of inflation is partly defended\nas the lesser of two evils.\nHowever, in the way in which the doctrine\nhas been received and discussed in business\ncircles, most of the emphasis seems to be on\nan alleged hopelessness of the struggle against\ninflation, with little emphasis being put upon\nthe redeeming features which are a part of\nthe original doctrine. On balance then, the\ntalk about \u201ccreeping inflation\" seems at pres\nent to be adding to gloom, whether the theory\nitself is right or wrong.\nAlso, it seems evident that a frequent busi\nness concern over possible tendencies of rising\ncosts to threaten existing profit margins play\ned a part in the stock market reaction which\nset in about mid-July. The latter, in turn, has\nadded to moods of pessimism.\nTHE OTHER SIDE: All of this sounds\nvery dark. Identifying the worries, however,\ndoes not necessarily imply agreeing with\nthem. Are there any answers to these anxie\nties? It is clear that there are no simple and\nfoolproof answers; otherwise the solutions\nwould be immediately known and the mists\nwould vanish. On the other hand, there are\npossible sources of reassurance concerning the\nmatters which have just been discussed. It is a\nmatter of judgment whether such reassur\nances are adequate. Let us sketch them, in\nany event, and leave it to each person to\nmake up his own mind as to how persuasive\nthey are.\nFirst as to the matter of defense cutbacks,\nseveral factors shoud be borne in mind. In\nthe first place, to the extent that the cutbacks\nare actually realized, they are counter-infla\ntionary in their effect It seems strange that\npeople who have in the past argued very\nstrongly for the need for Federal government\nretrenchment, on the ground of combatting\ninflation, sometimes turn out to be the very\nones who are seriously disturbed about the\neconomic Impact of the prospective defense\ncuts. Furthermore, it must surely be recog\nnised that intentions to reduce defense ex\npenditures, however sincere and determined\nare not always readily carried out or achiev\ned. The history of the last ten years is replete\nwith illustrations. International developments\namong other factors, often have a way of up\nsetting plans for retrenchment.\nSecond, as to the concern about the level-'\ning tendencies in plant and equipment, cer\ntain points should be kept in mind. There is as\nyet no positive evidence that the trend of\nthese outlays, which are currently at extreme\nly high levels, is shifting to a decline. Furth\nermore, there are rising tendencies in con\nsumer expenditures, and in outlays by State\nand local governments, which should be as\nsigned to the role of stimulating factors\nAs to the general inflationary worry, there\nare some things to be said on the other side.\nIn spite of the fact that prices generally have\ncontinued to rise, and in spite of the fact that\nthere is full justification for being concerned\nabout the matter, it does not follow that the\nwhole game has been lost. There has been a\ndefinite slowdown in the rate of rise in the\ngeneral price averages. There are cross-cur\nrents in the present price trends which may\nfinally result in over-all relief, without neces\nsarily precipitating a serious decline in busi\nness activity. There can, of course, be no\nguarantee of this outcome. Meanwhile, and\nuntil such time as the business trend takes a\nmore definite turn, it seems prudent that the\ngeneral policy of credit restraint should be\ncontinued.\nCLEVELAND REPUBLICANS held an\norganization workshop recently They\nheard the chief speaker say the GOP has\n\u201ca mature political philosophy which looks\nto the future\u201d The workshop was held\nin the House of Wills funeral home.\nYour Union\nAnd Mine\nBy RICHARD T. GOSSER\nVice President, UAW\nan\nON MANY OCCASIONS I have used this column to\nnounce some news or review some changes which\nwould help our members and which, I hoped, would bring\nthem happiness. I regret to say that my column this week\nisn\u2019t that kind.\nIt is with a heavy heart that I write this column because\nit deals with the closing of the Auto-Lite\u2019s Burt Foundry which\nwill go out of business within the next 30 to 90 days. First off\nI want to say that there -never has existed in the Electric Auto\nLite Corp, a more loyal, willing or cooperative group of workers\nthan the company had in the Burt Foundry. In my opinion man\nagement broke faith with the workers by not keeping the plant\nin a competitive position.\nThere is no use anymore to engage in any debate about this\nsituation. The thing that has to be done is to give our brothers\nin Burt Foundry as much help and cooperation as we can so they\ncan salvage as much as possible out of this situation. This is my\npurpose in writing this column\u2014to let Burt Foundry workers\nknow what their rights are and to have them take full advantage\nof them.\nBecause workers in Burt Foundry joined our Union they\ngained some privileges which cannot be lost or taken away even\nthough the company is closing up the shop. Yet these rights\naren't as much as I would like them to be.\nTO BEGIN WITH everyone\u2019s pension rights will be pro\ntected. Those fellows 63 years of age and over can immediately\nretire under the Pension Plan our Union has gained in this shop.\nThose who are 60 to 65 can apply for early retirement, if they\nso desire. However, this is a decision you must make as indivi\nduals. All members who have worked in the plant 10 years or\nmore and have reached age 40 have qualified for equity in the\nPension Plan. No one will lose this equity and when they reach\nthe retirement age of 65, they will get the pension credits they\nhave earned.\nNow for some more rights that Burt Foundry workers have.\nOur National Agreement with Auto-Lite specifies that prefer\nence in hiring must be given to any Auto-Lite employee who\nsigns a slip stating their desire to work in any company plant\nwhich is putting on help. The Agreement gives preferential hir\ning rights in Auto-Lite plants to all Burt Foundry workers up\nto the age of 68. This means that those Burt Foundry workers\nwho haven\u2019t reached 68 are eligible to apply for a job in an\nAuto-Lite plant that is hiring help.\nI recognize the hardship and the sacrifices that are involved\nwhen a worker is displaced and has to move from one town to\nanother, but some people may feel doing this is better than being\nout of work. It appears that very shortly Auto-Lite will be hir\ning people in its foundry in Fostoria, Ohio. Those people who\ngo there will carry all their pension and vacation credits with\nthem. Our National Agreement provides for this.\nIn saying this I know that moving to or commuting to\nFostoria entails hardship. But some people from Burt may prefer\neven this to being out of work. Again this is a decision for the\nindividual to make; I may suggest, too, that Burt Foundry work\ners might also like to seek employment in any of the other\nAuto-Lite plants that may be hiring.\n\nIF THERE ARE any Burt Foundry workers who do not un\nderstand their benefits, or who have a problem of any kind, I\nwant them to contact William Groeber, assistant director of the\nAuto-Lite Dept., UAW, at 425 Winthrop St. His office is on the\nfourth floor and his telephone number is CHerry 3-2451. If he\nis not in his secretary will arrange an appointment for you.\nI would have like to have talked to the Burt Foundry work\ners and given them this information at a special mass meeting\nfor them But unfortunately, experience has shown that a good\nmany people don\u2019t or won\u2019t show up for such a meeting. Be\ncause of this I am taking this means to get this information to\nyou. I hope, enough people will read it to pass the word along\nto the others who have missed it so they can read it, too.\nNo one can take any satisfaction from the Burt Foundry\nshutdown. This action by management is especially disappoint\ning to me and to all those who have joined with us in the Tole\ndo Industrial Development Council to attract new industry and\nthus create job opportunities. I know it will be small satisfac\ntion to Burt Foundry workers to say this, but it is important:\nBy being union members they have retained their precious\npension credits; and they have gained preferential hiring rights\nin other Auto-Lite plants to which they can bring their pension\nand vacation credits.\nI want to wish UAW Burt Foundry members the best of\nluck in their new endeavors. If I can help any of you in any\nway, don\u2019t hestitate to call me or drop a line. As always I shall\ncontinue to be at your service.\n00-.* Jem.\nVUww P WTSr% Cyv\nOpener\"\ne. ouY\nNUNN\n9 Can Be\nHeard Each\nY Weekday\nMorning At\n6:15 Ovei\nr CKLW.\n2 X\n20**8200 9\nBulletin\nBoard\u2014\nSaturday, October 5\nKIDS PARTY 10:00 A.M. Parlor A\nNATIONAL SUPPLY 1:30 P.M. Parlor A\nTOL. STEEL TUBE 10:00 A.M. Parlor B\nE. W. BLISS 1:30 P.M. Parlor H\nSunday, October 6\nSPICER STEWARDS 8:30 P.M. Parlor A\nSPICER MEMBERS 10:00 A.M. Parlor A\nMATHER 10:00 A.M. Parlor H\nMonday, October 7\nX TOLEDO WIRE PRODUCTS \u20148:00 P.M.\nParlor C\nTuesday, October 8\nSURFACE COMBUSTION 8:00 P.M. Parlor B\nBURT FOUNDRY 7:30 P.M. Parlor H\nWednesday, October 9\nJ&L (day) 7:00 P.M. Parlor A\nJ&L (night) 12:00 P.M. Parlor B\nSUPERIOR SPINNING 8:00 P.M. Parlor B\nRANSOM RANDOLPH \u20147:30 P.M. Parlor C\nThursday, October 19\nWOMEN\u2019S GUILD 8:00 P.M. Parlor A\nACME 8:00 P.M. Parlor B\nCAMERA CLUB 8:00 P M. Parlor C\nDARLING \u20148:00 P.M.\u2014 Room 309\nFriday, October 11\nLOCAL 12 8:00 P.M. Parlor A\nBOARD OF GOVERNORS 7:00 P.M. Parlor B\nLocal 12 Dues Office Open All Week Mon. Thru Fri.\nFrom 9:30 A.M. To 6:00 P.M. Closed All Day Sat., Sun.\nAnd All Holidays.","height":"26788","width":"19536"}}
